species species species of litter contained in litter bag
h2o_depth water depth (cm) water depth recorded at the litter bag site at retrieval
cell_num cell number cells were numbered 1 to 10 from west to east in the diked study area.

lb_site litter bag site litter bag sites represented the natural depth range for each species as observed during the 1987 growing season. Sites established in 1985 were used if they met this criteria; otherwise, new sites were established where previous sites had sparse or absent vegetation.
lb_num litter bag number number assigned to litter bag, in order to keep track of sample
day_in day litter bag deployed litter bags were deployed on one of three dates: 30-May-1988, 31-May-1988 and 1-June-1988;
month_in month litter bag deployed litter bags were deployed on one of three dates: 30-May-1988, 31-May-1988 and 1-June-1988;
year_in year litter bag deployed litter bags were deployed on one of three dates: 30-May-1988, 31-May-1988 and 1-June-1988;
fresh_wt fresh litter bag weight (g) Samples were dried to a constant weight (approx. 48 hours) at room temperature (20 degrees C), and approximately 10g was placed in a litter bag.
final_odw litter dry weight at collection (oven dry weight; g) samples were dried to a constant weight at 80 degrees C.
day_out day litter bag retrieved five collection dates: 1-June-1988 to 3-June-1988, 25-July-1988, 22-September-1988, 6-June-1989 to 7-June-1989, and 9-Aug-1989 to 11-Aug-1989
month_out month litter bag retrieved five collection dates: 1-June-1988 to 3-June-1988, 25-July-1988, 22-September-1988, 6-June-1989 to 7-June-1989, and 9-Aug-1989 to 11-Aug-1989
year_out year litter bag retrieved five collection dates: 1-June-1988 to 3-June-1988, 25-July-1988, 22-September-1988, 6-June-1989 to 7-June-1989, and 9-Aug-1989 to 11-Aug-1989
grnd_num ground number corresponds to subsample number ground for nutrient analysis

p_conc phosphorus concentration (mg/g) litter nutrient concentration; To reduce the number of samples analyzed for total carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus, ground samples were pooled by species, water depth and collection date prior to chemical analysis. When possible, five litter bag samples were combined to make 1 sample for nutrient analysis. Water depths were stratified into 30-cm intervals: i.e. 0 cm = unflooded, 1- 30 cm = shallow, 31-60 cm = medium,  60-90 cm = deep sites, and >90cm.

spec_code species code All macroinvertebrates were sorted to the appropriate taxonomic level required to determine trophic level, and the total number of each taxon was recorded. Identification to family was adequate, however Chironomidae were further classified to the Tanypodinae subfamily (predator) and all other subfamilies as Non-Tanypodinae (herbivore).
dev_stage developmental stage 0

trop_level trophic level Due to taxonomic problems with the invertebrates of wetlands and the overlap of the trophic categories suggested by Cummins (1973), 2 broad trophic levels were distinguished as herbivore-detrivore and predator-parasite.
indv_samp total individuals in sample To sort the individuals found in the activity traps, the rinsed samples were placed into a sorting tray and covered with a sugar solution. dimensionless

total_biomass_mg total biomass of sample (mg) A representative sample of all invertebrate taxa and size classes from all sorted samples (with the exception of emergence trap samples) were kept to determine biomass. The representative individuals were from each taxa and sample type were rinsed with distilled water and then placed in weighed and dried (105C for 24 hrs.) aluminum pans. The invertebrates were then dried at 105 C overnight and the pans were weighed again the following day. When 500 individuals of the same taxon or size class had been collected and weighed, where the mean weight was < 1.0mg, and 200 individuals from any taxa had a mean weight > 1.0 mg, these groups no longer had to be dried for their dry-weight determination (Ross and Murkin, 1989).
species code invertebrate species code seven-digit species code can be further divided into taxons of specific levels

Species name Macrophyte species name At the beginning of the belowground macrophyte production study (1980-1982), roots and rhizomes were categorized into species.

day sampling day In order to estimate net annual belowground macrophyte production, core samples of the belowground biomass were harvested in the late spring and in the fall. Shoot initiation early in the growing season depletes most of the belowground standing crop, and therefore spring sampling was done quickly (within 2 weeks) to capture this state. Underground biomass then reaches its seasonal maxima in the fall and was captured with the fall sampling.

T T IButton Thermochron temperature loggers (Maxim Inc., Dallas, TX) were buried at each grid point to a depth of 10 cm and temperature was logged for three days in continuous 30 min intervals. Mean soil temperatures at 10 cm depths were obtained for the three days of measurements and normalized within a measurement period. Higher soil temperature estimated from this normalization indicated that soil temperature at a particular microsite was higher than the mean of the 50 grid points. season Season Season (winter, spring, summer and autumn as defined by the winter solstice, spring equinox, summer solstice and autumnal equinox) in which the site is sampled.

NPP_wet NPP Wet The seasonal rate of M. pyrifera biomass production in units of wet mass (kg m-2 day-1). This variable is calculated by integrating the instantaneous rate of production during each period and dividing by the number of days (as described in Section I.B Equation 2). Production for all days in each season is averaged. kilogramPerMeterSquaredPerDay

NPP_dry NPP Dry The seasonal rate of M. pyrifera biomass production in units of dry mass (kg m-2 day-1). This variable is calculated by integrating the instantaneous rate of production during each period and dividing by the number of days (as described in Section I.B Equation 2). Production for all days in each season is averaged. kilogramPerMeterSquaredPerDay

NPP_carbon NPP Carbon The seasonal rate of M. pyrifera biomass production in units of carbon mass (kg m-2 day-1). This variable is calculated by integrating the instantaneous rate of production during each period and dividing by the number of days (as described in Section I.B Equation 2). Production for all days in each season is averaged. kilogramPerMeterSquaredPerDay

NPP_nitrogen NPP Nitrogen The seasonal rate of M. pyrifera biomass production in units of nitrogen mass (kg m-2 day-1). This variable is calculated by integrating the instantaneous rate of production during each period and dividing by the number of days (as described in Section I.B Equation 2). Production for all days in each season is averaged. kilogramPerMeterSquaredPerDay

Growth_rate_wet Growth rate, wet The seasonal growth rate of M. pyrifera wet mass (day-1). This variable is calculated as the growth rate necessary to explain the observed change in biomass during each period, given the initial biomass and the independently measured loss rates (see Section I.B Equation 1). Growth rates for all days in each season are averaged. reciprocalDay

Growth_rate_dry Growth rate, dry The seasonal growth rate of M. pyrifera dry mass (day-1). This variable is calculated as the growth rate necessary to explain the observed change in biomass during each period, given the initial biomass and the independently measured loss rates (see Section I.B Equation 1). Growth rates for all days in each season are averaged. reciprocalDay

Growth_rate_carbon Growth rate, carbon The seasonal growth rate of M. pyrifera carbon mass (day-1). This variable is calculated as the growth rate necessary to explain the observed change in biomass during each period, given the initial biomass and the independently measured loss rates (see Section I.B Equation 1). Growth rates for all days in each season are averaged. reciprocalDay

Growth_rate_nitrogen Growth rate, nitrogen The seasonal growth rate of M. pyrifera nitrogen mass (day-1). This variable is calculated as the growth rate necessary to explain the observed change in biomass during each period, given the initial biomass and the independently measured loss rates (see Section I.B Equation 1). Growth rates for all days in each season are averaged. reciprocalDay

SE_NPP_wet Std error, NPP wet The standard error in our estimate of NPP in units of wet mass (kg m-2 d-1). This error is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in Section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. It incorporates errors in estimates of biomass, plant loss rates and frond loss rates. kilogramPerMeterSquaredPerDay

Site Site code forsampling location
date date Date of collection
frnd_dens Frond Density Density of fronds of M. pyrifera numberPerMeterSquared

FSC_wet FSC Wet The wet mass of the foliar standing crop of M. pyrifera (kg m-2, excluding sporophylls and holdfast). These data are obtained by first calculating the wet mass of each plant, using methods detailed in Section I.B Measuring standing crop, and then dividing the total wet mass of all plants in the plot by the area of the plot. Plants without at least one frond longer than 1m are excluded. kilogramPerMeterSquared

FSC_dry FSC Dry The dry mass of the foliar standing crop of M. pyrifera (kg m-2, excluding sporophylls and holdfast). These data are obtained by first calculating the dry mass of each plant, using methods detailed in Section I.B Measuring standing crop, and then dividing the total dry mass of all plants in the plot by the area of the plot. Plants without at least one frond longer than 1m are excluded. kilogramPerMeterSquared

FSC_carbon FSC Carbon The carbon mass of the foliar standing crop of M. pyrifera (kg m-2, excluding sporophylls and holdfast). These data are obtained by first calculating the carbon mass of each plant, using methods detailed in Section I.B Measuring standing crop, and then dividing the total carbon mass of all plants in the plot by the area of the plot. Plants without at least one frond longer than 1m are excluded. kilogramPerMeterSquared

FSC_nitrogen FSC Nitrogen The nitrogen mass of the foliar standing crop of M. pyrifera (kg m-2, excluding sporophylls and holdfast). These data are obtained by first calculating the nitrogen mass of each plant, using methods detailed in Section I.B Measuring standing crop, and then dividing the total nitrogen mass of all plants in the plot by the area of the plot. Plants without at least one frond longer than 1m are excluded. kilogramPerMeterSquared
Frond_density Frond Density The density of M. pyrifera fronds in the plot (number m-2). numberPerMeterSquared
Plant_density Plant Density The density of M. pyrifera plants in the plot (number m-2). Only plants with at least one frond greater than 1m are counted.mv numberPerMeterSquared

Plant_loss_rate Plant Density The loss rate of M. pyrifera plants during the sampling interval (fraction of plants lost day-1). These data are based on losses of 10 to15 tagged plants, as described in Section I.B Measuring loss rate. reciprocalDay

Frond_loss_rate Frond loss rate The average loss rate of fronds during the sampling interval (fraction of fronds lost day-1). These data are the mean loss rate of tagged fronds from 10 to15 tagged plants, as described in Section I.B Measuring loss rate. The mean is based on frond loss from plants that survive the period; losses of whole plants are accounted for in the plant loss rate. reciprocalDay

SE_FSC_wet SE FSC Wet The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of wet mass (kg m-2). This estimate is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in Section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. The error in wet mass includes two types of error. Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass conversion ratio kilogramPerMeterSquared

SE_FSC_dry SE FSC Dry The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of dry mass (kg m-2). This estimate is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. The error in dry mass includes two types of error. Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass and wet-mass:dry-mass conversion ratios. kilogramPerMeterSquared

SE_FSC_carbon SE FSC Carbon The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of carbon mass (kg m-2). This estimate is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in Section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. The error in carbon mass includes two types of error. Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass, wet-mass:dry-mass and dry-mass:carbon-mass conversion ratios. kilogramPerMeterSquared

SE_FSC_nitrogen SE FSC Nitrogen The standard error in our estimate of foliar standing crop in units of nitrogen mass (kg m-2). This estimate is produced using Monte Carlo methods, as described in Section I.B Quantifying Uncertainty. The error in nitrogen mass includes two types of error. Observer error consists of errors made in the number of plants sampled and in the measurement of their size. Regression errors include variability in the allometric relationships used to calculate the size of the three plant sections, as well as uncertainty in the length:wet-mass, wet-mass:dry-mass and dry-mass:nitrogen-mass conversion ratios. kilogramPerMeterSquared

SE_Frond_density SE Frond Density The standard error in our estimate of M. pyrifera frond density (number m-2). Error in frond density reflects variation in the total number of plants sampled in a plot. This estimate is produced by comparing repeated sampling by different observers of a single plot. numberPerMeterSquared

SE_Plant_density SE Plant Density The standard error in our estimate of M. pyrifera plant density (number m-2). Error in plant density reflects variation in the total number of plants sampled in a plot. This estimate is produced by comparing repeated sampling by different observers of a single plot. numberPerMeterSquared

SE_Plant_loss_rate SE Plant Loss Rate The standard error in our estimate of M. pyrifera plant loss (day-1). This error is sampling error associated with calculating a mean loss rate for the entire plot based on 10 to15 tagged plants. reciprocalDay

SE_Frond_loss_rate SE Frond Loss Rate The standard error in the calculated rate of frond loss (day-1). This error is sampling error associated with calculating a mean loss rate for the entire plot based on 10 to15 tagged plants. reciprocalDay

Longitude  The longitude of the location from which the Symbiodinium specimen was collected. This value should be expressed in decimal degrees (East & North = +; West & South = -). GPS-derived data must use the WGS 84 geodetic reference system. degree

Coordinate_Precision Coordinate precision An estimate of how tightly the locality was specified in the Latitude and Longitude fields; expressed as a distance, in meters, that corresponds to a radius around the latitude-longitude coordinates. Use NULL where precision is unknown, cannot be estimated, or is not applicable. meter

Min_Depth The minimum distance in meters below the surface of the water at which the collection/record was made; all material collected was at least this deep. Positive below the surface, negative above (e.g. collecting above sea level in tidal areas).

Max_Depth  The maximum distance in meters below the surface of the water at which the collection/record was made; all material collected was at most this deep. Positive below the surface, negative above (e.g. collecting above sea level in tidal areas). meter

Start_Year_Collect  For samples that were taken over time this gives the start year of the collecting event. The full year should be expressed (e.g. 1996 must be expressed as "1996" not "96"). Must always be a four digit integer

End_Year_Collect  For samples that were taken over time this gives the end year of the collecting event. The full year should be expressed (e.g. 1996 must be expressed as "1996" not "96"). Must always be a four digit integer. If specimen was collected in a single calendar year then enter the same value in this field as in Start_Year_Collect.

BNr_ Baumnummer Zur eindeutigen Identifikation wurde eine fortlaufende Baumnummer vergeben. Nummeriert wurde von Nord nach Sued und sofern noetig von West nach Ost (hangaufwaerts). Der Nummernkreis beginnt bei 0001 und endete an der Versuchsflaeche Ringelsberg bei 0046. Die Totale jedes einzelbaumes wurde fotografiert und ist unter der Baumnummer archiviert.
Lage Nummerierung Nummerierung der Habitate je Baum. Zaehlung beginnt am Stammfuss.
Hoehe Hoehe der Struktur Hoehe der Struktur Lotrecht vom Erdboden aus.Angabe in ganzen Metern. meter
Exposition  Angabe der Himmelsrichtung in welche das Habitat exponiert ist. (N, NO, O, SO, S, SW, W, NW, Z zentral)
SKZ Strukturkennziffer 01 Spechthoehlen

Str_Nr_ Strukturnummer Jede Struktur erhaelt eine eindeutige Identifikationsnummer die sich aus der Baumnummer, der Lagenummer, der Strukturennziffer und einer Pruefziffer zusammensetzt. Anwender sollen so in die Lage versetzt werden anhand dieser Nummer die wichtigsten Informationen zum Habitat anhand der Nummer zu erkennen. Die 9 Stellige Strukturnummer setzt sich wie folgt zusammen: 0001: 4 stellige Baumnummer, nach Grunderfassungsdaten 01 : 2 stellige Lagenummer, Habitate werden nummeriert gezaehlt wird vom Boden aus. 11 : Strukturkennziffer, wie unter Spalte 5 definiert. 1 : Strukturabfrage, 1 = Habitat besteht in der Form 0 = Habitat wurde geaendert bzw. besteht in der Form nicht mehr. 0001-01-11-1 wuerde bedeuten eine kleine Spechthoehle an Baumnummer 1. Die Hoehle stellt die erste Struktur, vom Boden aus, im Baum dar und war auffindbar. Jede Struktur wurde Fotodokumwentiert und ist unter der Strukturnummer archiviert.
Info Information Zusaetzliche Informationen zu Habitatbewohnern, holzzersetzenden Pilzen, anthropogenen Spuren etc., die sonst nirgends erfasst wurden.

Focal Species  The Species and Protocols Group (S&P) applied a combination of desired criteria and applications to a comprehensive plant database (http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/) and has developed a list of about 150 species, which will be vetted by participating networks and programs. The primary goal of this selection is to establish a baseline of phenological patterns for plants and animals across the nation, help monitor and detect phenological responses to climate change, immediately demonstrate the national scope of network, and engage the largest possible number of participants within a backbone network.

Station Study Site Location Names These are the actual study site locations.

Long Dec Longitude of the study site Longitude of the study site degree
Nearby feature Geographic reference point for each study site. This provides a nearby reference point for each study reach.
Site Name of the study site This is the name of the study site.
Year This is the year that the sample was collected. This is the specific year that a sample was collected.
Month This is the month that a sample was collected. This is the particular month that a sample was collected.
Day This is the day of the month that a sample was collected. This is the day of the month that a particular sample was collected.
Date This is the date that a sample was collected. This is the specific date that a sample was collected.

Sample ID This is the unique identifier for each sample. These are the sample identifications that were recorded off of the lab datasheets. Note that some sites and year do not exhibit consecutive sampling numbers.  When a detrital depletion sample was taken, the first number in the column is the dome sample number.  The second number is the detrital sample number. The samples with the 'a' designation are the samples used for invertebrate calculations.  The samples with the 'b' or 'c' designation are the detrital depletion samples that were not used in the invertebrate calculations.

Sample Type This the sample type of the specific sample Two types of samples were identified.  Invert samples are the ones that were used for the invertebrate assemblage calculations.  The detrital depletion are replicate samples at the dome sampling sites, which were not used in the invertebrate calculations.
Sampler type This is the type of sample instrument used This is the type of instrument used to collect the sample.  In 1976, a modified kicknet was used.  In 1977, a dome sampler was used.
Habitat Habitat type where the sample was taken. This is the habitat type where a specific sample was taken.
Order Taxonomic order This is the taxonomic order that a particular individual belonged to
Family Taxonomic family This is the taxonomic family that an individual was classified as
Genus Taxonomic genus This is the genus that an individual was classified as
Species Taxomic species designation This is the species name of the particular organism
Stage Development stage This is the development stage that an individual was classified as.

# in Size Fraction  1mm or  500um (# per sample) Abundance of individuals in the large size fraction This is the number of individuals per sample.  In 1976, this was defined as individuals   1mm.  In 1977, this was defined as individuals   500micrometers. number per sample

# in Size Fraction <1mm and 100m (# per sample) # in the smaller size fraction This is the total number of individuals of a particular taxonomic group that was found in the smaller size fraction of that sample.  In 1977, this was defined as <500micrometer and 100micrometer.  This size fraction was not collected during 1976. number per sample
Area sampled (cm^2) The sample area This is the area of the benthos that was sampled for a given sample. squareCentimeters

Habitat Notes Notes on the substrate and habitat of a particular sample This reports the dominant substrate or habitat that was present at a given sampling location.  Also, this indicates which invert sample that a detrital depletion sample was coupled with.

ID notes Notes about the old taxonomic name for a particular organism Between the 1970s and the present, taxonomic names have changed.  The name reported here is the name originally reported in the RCC publications, which has been updated in the genus column.
Sample Date The date a sample was taken This is the date that sample was collected
Site Study site name This is the RCC study site
Sample processing notes Notes on how and which samples were size fractionated This describes the sampling method used.  It also indicates which samples were size fractionated and picked.

INSTITUTIONCODE  The code (or acronym) identifying the institution administering the collection in which the organism record is cataloged. No global registry exists for institutional codes; use the code that is "standard" in your discipline.
COLLECTIONCODE  The code (or acronym) identifying the collection within the institution in which the organism record is cataloged.

CATALOGNUMBER  The alphanumeric value identifying an individual organism record within the collection. It is highly recommended that each record is uniquely identified within a collection by this value.
OCCURRENCEID  The identifier for the occurrence constructed from: InstitutionCode, CollectionCode and CatalogNumber.
RECORDEDBY  The identity code of the individual reporting the observation.
YEAR  The four digit year in the Common Era calendar in which the organism was collected from the field.
MONTH  The two digit month of year in the Common Era calendar during which the organism was collected from the field.
DAY  The two digit day of the month in the Common Era calendar during which the organism was collected from the field.
COUNTRY  The full, unabbreviated name of the country or major political unit from which the organism was collected.
STATEPROVINCE  The full, unabbreviated name of the state, province, or region (i.e., the next smaller political region than Country) from which the organism was collected.
COUNTY  The full, unabbreviated name of the county, shire, or municipality (i.e., the next smaller political region than StateProvince) from which the organism was collected.
DECIMALLATITUDE  The latitude of the location from which the organism was collected, expressed in decimal degrees. degree
DECIMALLONGITUDE  The longitude of the location from which the organism was collected, expressed in decimal degrees. degree
LOCALITY  The specific description of the place the observation occurred.
KINGDOM  The name of the taxonomic kingdom in which the organism is classified.
PHYLUM  The name of the taxonomic phylum (or division) in which the organism is classified.
CLASS  The name of the taxonomic class in which the organism is classified.
ORDER  The name of the taxonomic order in which the organism is classified.
FAMILY  The name of the taxonomic family in which the organism is classified.
GENUS  The name of the taxonomic genus in which the organism is classified.
SPECIFICEPITHET  The name of the taxonomic species in which the organism is classified.

attribute: Further details  Further details

Recno  A unique number representing each bird observation. This includes an observation of no birds when no birds were seen or heard at a sample point visit. The numbers are assigned sequentially to each observation as they are added to the Birds database (Access) for the Silvicultural Systems Trial (maintained by Forestry Tasmania). dimensionless

Samplecode  A unique number assigned to each visit to a sample point. Multiple records (Recno) with the same Samplecode occur when more than one bird species are detected in a visit. Each Samplecode is prefixed with the respective alphanumeric code of the treatment within the Silvicultural Systems Trial: All sample points along Bird Track are assigned the prefix EX.
Pointcode  A code assigned to each unique sample point. The twenty sample points monitored annually along Bird Track are assigned Pointcodes in the range EX01  EX021 (sample point EX019 is excluded).

Year  Year in which the survey was done. Most year records will span the months October  December (notably an exception is the 1998 survey, which was done in autumn). On a few occasions the final survey date will extend into January of the next year (but still assigned the previous year).
Date  The actual date the survey visit was made
Time of day  The time of day the survey visit was made

Acronym  An alphanumeric code unique to each bird species and derived as a compression of the accepted common name of that species. A lookup table of the full species binomical and common name assigned to each Acronym is given in the file  Bird_Track_Birds_1998_2010_Names.xls.

Incidence  A value of 1 / 0 denoting presence (1) of a bird species within 25 m of a sample point during a visit. An Incidence value of 0 is assigned if a species was observed from a sample point visit but at a distance of > 25m from the sample point. dimensionless

Number recorded  Number of individuals of a bird species observed together within 25 m of a sample point during a visit. Note: records of species observed at separate times during a five minute sample period are each assigned separate values of number recorded dimensionless
Distance  Estimated distance from the sample point to the bird observed meter
Height  Numeric code between 1-6 that represents the approximate height of the vertical stratum of the forest in which the observed bird occurred. number
Direction  Approximate bearing from the sample point to the bird record observed. Represented by a number between 1-8 representing successive 45 quadrants where 1 = N-NE. number

N_OBSERVED  number of observations actually observed in a sample number

N_MISSING  the number of values in a sampling period (year or month), given the intended sampling frequency (e.g., every 15 minutes, every day, etc.), that were not available for calculating statistics. N_ESTIMATED  the number of values in a sampling period (year or month) that were flagged as estimated number
N_TRACE  the number of values in a sampling period (year or month) that were flagged as trace values (this is only used for precipitation data) number
N_INVALID  according to some testing criteria outlined in the summarization script (e.g., temp > 75 degrees C) number

Site Site Site Name: Name of the lake where measurements were taken. There are discrete sampling sites defined by water depth, generally they are at the point of maximum depth.

Time_hr_dst Time_hr_dst Exact time that each reading was recorded in Alaska Daylight Savings Time (1 hour ahead of Alaska Standard Time: if 13:00 DST than 12:00 AST)
IBVSvr4a_V IBVSvr4a_V Internal Battery Voltage of the Surveyor 4a Datalogger. volt
Temp_C Temp_C Water temperature at depth. celsius
Cond_uS Cond_uS Electrical conductivity of the water at depth. microsiemenPerCentimeter
Dep_m Dep_m Depth of water measurement taken at starting from the surface as 0. meter
pH pH pH (opposite of the log of the hydrogen ion concentration). dimensionless
DO_Sat DO_Sat The percent saturation of dissolved oxygen at depth. percent
DO_mg/l DO_mg/l The concentration of dissolved oxygen at depth. milligramPerLiter
Chl_V Chl_V In Vivo measurement of chlorophyll-a concentration. volt
Chl_ug/l Chl_ug/l In Vivo measurement of chlorophyll-a concentration. microgramPerLiter
PAR_uEm2s PAR_uEm2s PAR (photosynthetically active radiation) measured below the water surface. microEinsteinPerMeterSquaredPerSecond
refPAR_uEm2s refPAR_uEm2s PAR (photosynthetically active radiation) measured with Deck unit to correct for changes in ambient light. microEinsteinPerMeterSquaredPerSecond
Secchi_m Secchi_m Measure of water transparency by depth a Secchi Disk is visible to. meter
Hydrolab Hydrolab This field indicates which Hydrolab Datasonde instrument was used to take measurements
Notes Notes Any additional information pertaining to measurments made for a particular depth, place and time.

flag  data flag used to qualify data as bad, questionable, etc.
date  Greenwich Mean Time calendar date of each ADCP measurement record, using ISO 8601 standard format YYYY-MM-DD

time  Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, to the 1/100th of a second, using ISO 8601 standard format hh:mm:ss.ssZ.  The 'Z' indicates 'Zero Meridian' (or Greenwich Mean Time) and must be included.

yearday  Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, expressed as fractional decimal days since Jan. 1 of the year measurement was made.  For example, 12 noon GMT on Jan. 2 is represented by yearday 1.5, NOT yearday 2.5. nominalDay
height  The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom. meter
depth  The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL).  Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths. meter

waterdepth  The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity. meter
temp_c  seawater temperature from ADCP sensor celsius
pressure  pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument. decibar
intensity  ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts.  This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number. number
annotation_note: use like an N, count of observations.

attribute: data_quality  A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator.  Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc. number
eastward  True eastward velocity measurements.  Negative values represent westward velocities. metersPerSecond
northward  True northward velocity measurements.  Negative values represent southward velocities. metersPerSecond
upwards  True upwards velocity measurements.  Negative values represent downward velocities. metersPerSecond
errorvelocity  The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams metersPerSecond

river name river "river" is the name of the river, floodplain, or esutary system where flow has been manipulated.
facility name facility "facility name" is the dam of the dam or other structure used to manipulate flow. In situations where there are multiple dams, only the downstream dam may be listed.
operator operator "operator" is the agency or utility that operates the facility.
state-province state-province "state-province" is the political subdivision of the country where the facility is located.
county country Country where facility is located. Note that river systems may span multiple countries.
longitude longitude "longitude" is the longitude of the facility measured east ofthe Prime Meridian, Greenwich, England. Negative values are west of the Prime Meridian. degree
latitude latitude "latitude" is the latitude of the facility measured relative to the equator. degree
primary-purpose-of-facility purpose "primary-purpose-of-facility" is the water management use of the facility

mean-unregulated-streamflow streamflow "unregulated-streamflow' is the volumetric flux rate of water that would flow through the river channel at the location of the facility if the facility did not regulate flow averaged for a multiple-year period cubicMetersPerSecond

period-of-record-unregulated-streamflow period-unregulated Years of recorded used to calculate mean-unregulated-streamflow. These may be water years (1 Oct - 30 Sept) or calendar years depending on the source. nominalYear
type of intake structure intake-structure "intake-structure" is the location of the intake on a dam indicating whether water released from the dam is from the reservoir surface or hypolimnion.
dam-height dam-height The height of the dam meter

maximum-storage-volume maximum-storage The maximum volume of water stored in the reservoir. Reported maximum storage may be either active storage (the volume of water that can be stored and released) or active storage + dead storage (the volume of water in the reservoir below the intake structure. Sedimentation is generally not accounted for in estimates of storage. miillion cubic meters
mean-regulated-streamflow mean-regulated-streamflow Mean streamflow released from the facility over a multiple year period. cubicMetersPerSecond
period-of-record-regulated-streamflow period-regulated The years of record for regulated streamflow nominalYear

Geonor_HZ Geonor Precipitation Gage ferquency reading (Hertz) The Geonor Precipitation Gage uses a vibrating wire strain gage to measure the weight of precipitation accumulating in a rain can.  It produces a frequency signal in Hertz that is directlt proportional to the weight of the precipitation over the range of weights produced in the instrument. hertz

Geonor_precip_mm Geonor Total Precipitation (mm) Total precipitation in milimeters since the last re-set of the rain gage.  The rain can is emptied twice a year, just before the monsoons start and just after they end.  This running count provides a way to know whether the rain can is filling up. The Geonor Precipitation Gage uses a vibrating wire strain gage to measure the weight of precipitation accumulating in a rain can.  It produces a frequency signal in Hertz that is directlt proportional to the weight of the precipitation over the range of weights produced in the instrument. millimeter

LATITUDE  Latitude in decimal degrees degree

STATION  Alpha-numeric designation for the Station established in the design of a Survey.
STRATUM  RACE database statistical area for analyzing data. Strata were designed using bathymetry and other measures of habitat and are unique to each survey series.
YEAR  Year specimen was collected.

DATETIME  Date. This is the date and time at the beginning of the haul; For groundfish trawl data, this is the on-bottom time which is determined after we have looked at the bottom-contact sensor and net-mensuration plots. For hydroacoustic data, start_time is when the first fish is captured (displayed on the net sounder) or when the net is at target depth and location.
WTCPUE  Catch weight per area the net swept in KG/HA. kilogramsPerHectare
NUMCPUE  Catch number per area the net swept in number/HA. numberPerHectare

SCIENTIFIC  The scientific name of the organism associated with the COMMON_NAME.
SID  Species code number as defined in RACE Species Codebook; http://www.afsc.noaa.gov/RACE/groundfish/species_codebook.pdf

BOT_DEPTH  Meters (m). Weighted average depth (m) and is calculated by adding GEAR_DEPTH to NET_HEIGHT. Prior to (year), before NET_HEIGHT was regularly measured, this value was obtained using either echosounder or bathythermograph. meter
BOT_TEMP  Weighted average temperature (in tenths of a degree Celsius) measured at the maximum depth of the headrope of the trawl. Null values indicate temperature not recoreded. celsius
SURF_TEMP  Surface temperature, in tenths of a degree, Celsius. Null values indicate temperature not recorded. celsius
VESSEL  Vessel code based on Domain: RACE ADP Codebook: Vessel Codes; http://www.afsc.noaa.gov/RACE/groundfish/adp_codebook.pdf

CRUISE  This is a six-digit number identifying the Cruise number. It is of the form: YYYY99 (where YYYY = year of the cruise; 99 = 2-digit number and is sequential; 01 denotes the first cruise that vessel made in this year, 02 is the second, etc.)
HAUL  This number uniquely identifies a haul within a cruise. It is a sequential number, in chronological order of occurrence. dimensionless

d_n  D (day) is defined as the time between local sunrise and sunset, while N (night) is defined as the time between local sunset and sunrise. The time of the midpoint of the sample is used to designate the sample as day or night. Its important because the CPR sample is at a fixed depth, but some zooplankton migrate upwards at night, therefore some taxa are only sampled at night. For some statistics you will need to know the proportion of day versus night samples in a particular region and time frame.

date  Position, date and time information of the sample is taken from ships log information and refers to the midpoint of the 18.5 km sample. Constant speed between log entries is assumed (and in practice this is quite accurate on the scale that the CPR is deployed over since commercial ships tend to run at constant speed between ports).

lat  Position, date and time information of the sample is taken from ships log information and refers to the midpoint of the 18.5 km sample. Constant speed between log entries is assumed (and in practice this is quite accurate on the scale that the CPR is deployed over since commercial ships tend to run at constant speed between ports). degree

long  Position, date and time information of the sample is taken from ships log information and refers to the midpoint of the 18.5 km sample. Constant speed between log entries is assumed (and in practice this is quite accurate on the scale that the CPR is deployed over since commercial ships tend to run at constant speed between ports). degree
taxonIDNumber  CPR identification number assigned to taxonomic entities (http://www.sahfos.ac.uk/data_specieslist.htm)

analysisStage  Microscopic processing stage. Zooplankton counts are recorded for all species and specimen types in each sample. CPR sample analysis is reported for two zooplankton stages: "eyecount" and "traverse". "Eyecount"= zooplankton larger than 2mm; whole sample is checked by eye for presence of species, which are then removed from the sample to be identified under the microscope. "Traverse"= zooplankton smaller than 2mm; sub sample under lower magnification; traverse of the sample is made by microscope, and all individuals are counted.
planktonType  Indicates phyoplankton or zooplankton being analyzed in the sample

NEWSpeciesName Revised taxonomic name The current revised taxonomic name. Allows samples taken before the name change to be matched with data from after the name change. Otherwise it might appear in a time series that an organism disappeared, and another one appeared, when in fact they are the same.
OLDSpeciesName  Species name or specimen type identified in sample, from historic data

speciesCountCategory  The zooplankton abundances are given in categories for eyecount and traverse methods e.g. eyecount category 4 contains between 4 and 11 individuals. Colour= 0, 1, 2, 3 (relates to green colour of the mesh) and phytoplankton= 1-10 (number of fields of view divided by two and expressed as an integer). Sometimes an organism is too rare to be counted in its correct analysis stage but is seen in a subsequent analysis stage. It is recorded as "present" to show that it was there, but not abundant enough to be counted. For full definitions see the Table fo Accepted Values for phytoplankton (_p) and zooplankton (_z).

Cruise_Code  Unique identifier for this cruise, created from Research_Group + Date_Effort + Vessel
Autonum  Automatic numbering, user has no control over this and that's okay number
Research_Group  Four letter code unique to each research group, example: "GB, HMMC, TDI, HNS"
Date_Effort  Date of effort
Vessel  Research vessel for this effort. Needs to be here in case a research group sends out more than one vessel per day"
Cruise_Type  Explains if this is a SPLASH dedicated cruise, or opportunistic data

Region  4-letter abbreviation for large geographic location in Alaska (NGOA = northern Gulf of Alaska, EGOA = eastern Gulf of Alaska - dividing line is at Cape Suckling), see ltblStudyArea
Start_Location  Location where survey began.  Enter full place name of harbor or mooring or enter 3-letter place name from ltblPlace_Names.
End_Location  Location where survey ended.  Enter full place name of harbor or mooring or enter 3-letter place name from ltblPlace_Names.
Start_Time_for_Day  Legacy data - not on current data entry form.  What time did effort start for the day? This can happen more than once during the day if there are breaks.

Cruise_Start  Departure time from harbor or mooring (regardless of whether or not you were on effort). Use 24-hour clock (hh:mm)
Cruise_End  Arrival time at harbor or mooring (regardless of whether or not you were on effort).  Use 24-hour clock (hh:mm)

Nautical_Miles_Travelled  Use the GPS track log to determine or estimate how many nautical miles were covered during today's cruise from beginning to end (e.g., port to port), so this may include some miles off effort. nauticalMile

procite  The citations are linked to a ProCite database. The ProCite database record number corresponds to the Excel Procite Number. number
resource  A generic, biological resource describing the species studied
reference  Referenced citations included unpublished and published materials, magazine articles, dissertations, journal articles, books, maps, environmental impact statements, websites, and CD-ROMs.
reviewLevel  The citations level of critical review was denoted as reviewed or unknown.

region  A general location was assigned to each study which included the following: Gulf of Alaska (GOA), western Gulf of Alaska (WGOA), eastern Gulf of Alaska (EGOA), Cook Inlet (CIK), Kodiak Island (KOD), Alaska Peninsula (AKP), Prince William Sound (PWS), eastern Prince William Sound (EPWS), western Prince William Sound (WPWS), and Cooper River Delta (CRD). The Gulf of Alaska study area encompasses the region between Chignik, Alaska, and Yakutat, Alaska.
area  If reported, specific location was listed (e.g. Green Is., Nelson Bay, Pt. Valdez).
sitesArea  The number of study sites per project. A . was entered for any cell with an unknown or not applicable status. dimensionless
inferenceScale  Projects concentrated on the regional (e.g. GOA), area (e.g. Montague Island), or site level (e.g. Island Flats).
actual  An n for no (generic) or y for yes (actual) states if the lat/long was an exact or estimated location.

lat  The latitudes and longitudes were recorded to the 5th decimal. A GPS unit or GIS mapping tool were used to determine the lat/longs for each study. If a study covered a large area, one generic, centralized location was recorded. degree

long  The latitudes and longitudes were recorded to the 5th decimal. A GPS unit or GIS mapping tool were used to determine the lat/longs for each study. If a study covered a large area, one generic, centralized location was recorded. degree

radius  Values in the radius field represent areas of inference, or the geographic scale at which the sampling described in each reference represents. For example a survey of sea otters in all of Prince William Sound would be represented by a single latitude /longitude in the center of the Sound, but with a radius of 100 km to indicate the geographic extent of the survey. These radii are referred to as buffer.shp themes for each resource theme in the ArcView product. It is probably not useful to display buffers.shp themes until themes that represent subsets of the full resource are created, as they may obscure points. Radii values range from 5 to 1000 km. kilometer
classificationLevel  The lowest taxonomic level was identified to phylum, class, or species.
class1  Identification to the genus taxonomic level.
class2  Identification to the species taxonomic level.
depth  Only intertidal (inter) or subtidal (ssub) depths were recorded. Ssub was used only when specifically mentioned or illustrated within an article.
metric  The metrics describe what data a project collected
startYear  First year of the study
endYear  Last year of the study
numberYears  Number of years of the study nominalYear
season  A year was separated into the following seasons: Winter (November  March), Spring (April  mid-May), Summer (mid-May  August), and Fall (September  October).

sampleYears  The specific years the project was conducted. An all was entered for any long-term, continuous study. An unknown (U) was entered when a project neglected to cite the specific study years.
method  The methods describe how the data was collected

fattyAcid  Fatty acid name

relativeAbundance  In Project 769, we were comparing the fatty acid compositions of different herring stocks, so the value listed for each fatty acid represents that FA's relative abundance among all the FA's quantified for that sampled herring (SIN).  For each fish sampled (i.e., row) there were up to 25 different fatty acids identified.  When you add up each FA's relative contribution to the total, you get 100%.

titerStrength  A titer (or titre) is a way of expressing concentration. Titer testing employs serial dilution to obtain approximate quantitative information from an analytical procedure that inherently only evaluates as positive or negative. The titer corresponds to the highest dilution factor that still yields a positive reading. For example, positive readings in the first 8 serial twofold dilutions translate into a titer of 1:256 (i.e., 28). Titers are sometimes expressed by the denominator only, for example 1:256 is written 256.

DeployID Deployment Identifier A unique animal I.D. assigned by the user (ADF&G in this case).  It is made up of a concatenation of PV for Phoca vitulina (harbor seal), two numbers for the year of capture (e.g. 96 for the year 1996), 2-3 letters indicating the capture location (e.g. PWS for Prince William Sound), and lastly, the number assigned to the animal (1, 2, 325, etc.).
AltID Alternate Identifier Unknown ID of some sort only found in this file.  Please use the deployedID as the unique animal identifier as it is consistent throughout all spreadsheets.

PTT Argos Platform Transmitter Terminal identifier Argos Platform Transmitter Terminal identifier.  Note that the PTTs are reused through time.  You have to match this up with the Deploy ID number to identify individuals.
Date Date Date of message reception in UTC/GMT.  If the histogram was received multiple times, this will be the date and time of the latest reception.
Time Time Date of message reception in UTC/GMT.  If the histogram was received multiple times, this will be the date and time of the latest reception.
FormattedTime Formatted Time Time formatted to hh:mm:ss

State State "0" means the SDR was at the "on land" rate; "1" means the SDR was at the "at sea" rate.  The assumption is that when the sensor indicated wet (at sea) the seal was at sea, and when it indicated dry (on land) the seal was on land.

DeployID Deployment Identifier A unique animal I.D. assigned by the user (ADF&G in this case).  It is made up of a concatenation of PV for Phoca vitulina (harbor seal), two numbers for the year of capture (e.g. 96 for the year 1996), 2-3 letters indicating the capture location (e.g. PWS for Prince William Sound), and lastly, the number assigned to the animal (1, 2, 325, etc.).
Ptt Argos Platform Transmitter Terminal identifier Argos Platform Transmitter Terminal identifier.  Note that the PTTs are reused through time.  You have to match this up with the Deploy ID number.
Instr Instrument Family Wildlife Computers instrument family.  In this file, the only instrument family is ST16.

RecordType ARGOS Record Type Type of ARGOS record, either DS or DI.  The DS record contains the data that the tag transmitted along with the Argos calculated position, if a position could be calculated.  The DI record contains the results of the Argos calculated positions.
MsgCount Message Count Number of messages received from the PPT for the satellite pass. dimensionless
Duplicates Duplicates The number of identical messages received for the satellite pass.  A value of 1 means the original plus one duplicate was received.
Corrupt Corrupt Messages The number of corrupt messages in the given satellite pass. dimensionless
AvgInterval Average Interval The average inter-message interval in seconds of all received messages for the given satellite pass second
MinInterval Minimum Interval The minimum inter-message interval in seconds among received messages for a satellite pass second
dateTIme Date & Time Date and time of message reception in UTC/GMT.  It is not corrected for clock error or drift.
Satellite Satellite Name of the Argos satellite that received the message

LocationQuality Location Quality Location class assigned by Argos for the computed position.  Location classes are based on satellite/transmitter geometry during satellite pass, number of messages received during the pass, and transmitter frequency stability.
Latitude Latitude Latitude in Decimal degrees, computed by Argos. degree
Longitude Longitude Longitude in decimal degrees, calculated by Argos. degree
Latitude2 Latitude 2 Argos DI messages contain a second latitude value since their location algorithm can generate two possible positions.  This is the second latitude value. degree
Longitude2 Longitude 2 Argos DI messages contain a second longitude value since their location algorithm can generate two possible positions.  This is the second longitude value. degree
IQ  Argos-supplied value which gives transmitter frequency information. It should be interpreted as a two digit value in the form of XY whose meanings are:
Duration Duration Time elapsed between the first and last message received by the transmitter.
Frequency Frequency Calculated frequency of the transmitter. hertz
Power Signal Power The best received signal strength (dB) during the satellite pass dimensionless

transDuty Tag transmittion duty cycling Tags are programmed for what days they will transmit.  To extend the battery life, some tags are programmed to transmit less often (e.g. every other day instead of every day).  No duty means the tag is set to transmit every day. nominalDay

timeLocalGMT Local time corresponding to 00h GMT/UTC (0-23 hours) he tag is programmed with a GMT offset by the user.  The bin data is stored according to true local time based on the GMT offset.

fattyAcid  Fatty acid signature. A fatty acid is a carboxylic acid with a long aliphatic (carbon chain) tail which is either saturated (no double bonds between carbon pairs) or unsaturated (at least one double bond between carbon pairs). In the naming of fatty acids, lipid numbers take the form C:D, where C is the number of carbon atoms in the fatty acid chain and D is the number of double bonds in the fatty acid (if more than one, the double bonds are assumed to be interrupted by CH2 units, i.e., at intervals of 3 carbon atoms along the chain). This notation can be ambiguous, as some different fatty acids can have the same numbers. nx nomenclature both provides names for individual compounds and classifies them by their likely biosynthetic properties in animals. A double bond is located on the xth carboncarbon bond, counting from the terminal methyl carbon (designated as n toward the carbonyl carbon. For example: linolenic acid is written as 18:2 n-6, this means that there are 18 carbons in the fatty acid chain and there are 2 double bonds, with the first double bond occurring 6 carbons from the methyl end (between carbons 6 and 7) and the second would be at the 9th carbon (between carbons 9 and 10). Here is a drawing of the chemical structure for linolenic acid (18:2 n-6) CH3-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH=CH-CH2-CH=CH-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH2-CH2-COOH. i and ai stands for iso and anteiso, which are branched chain fatty acids, me stands for fatty acids that contain a methyl group, d stands for deoxy, and represents fatty acids with less oxygen atoms than normal.
amount  The amount represents each fatty acid's (FA's) relative abundance among all the FA's quantified for that sample dimensionless

Focal Species  The Species and Protocols Group (S&P) applied a combination of desired criteria and applications to a comprehensive plant database (http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/) and has developed a list of about 150 species, which will be vetted by participating networks and programs. The primary goal of this selection is to establish a baseline of phenological patterns for plants and animals across the nation, help monitor and detect phenological responses to climate change, immediately demonstrate the national scope of network, and engage the largest possible number of participants within a backbone network.

Focal Species  The Species and Protocols Group (S&P) applied a combination of desired criteria and applications to a comprehensive plant database (http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/) and has developed a list of about 150 species, which will be vetted by participating networks and programs. The primary goal of this selection is to establish a baseline of phenological patterns for plants and animals across the nation, help monitor and detect phenological responses to climate change, immediately demonstrate the national scope of network, and engage the largest possible number of participants within a backbone network.

flag  data flag used to qualify data as bad, questionable, etc.
date  Greenwich Mean Time calendar date of each ADCP measurement record, using ISO 8601 standard format YYYY-MM-DD

time  Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, to the 1/100th of a second, using ISO 8601 standard format hh:mm:ss.ssZ.  The 'Z' indicates 'Zero Meridian' (or Greenwich Mean Time) and must be included.

yearday  Greenwich Mean Time of each ADCP measurement record, expressed as fractional decimal days since Jan. 1 of the year measurement was made.  For example, 12 noon GMT on Jan. 2 is represented by yearday 1.5, NOT yearday 2.5. nominalDay
height  The height of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in meters above the sea bottom. meter
depth  The depth of the velocity, temperature, or pressure measurement, in positive meters below Mean Sea Level (MSL).  Bins above MSL are represented with negative depths. meter

waterdepth  The fluctuating water depth (sea floor to sea surface distance) at the measurement site, in meters, as determined by location of sea surface from ADCP pressure measurements, or if pressure is unavailable, the maximum in ADCP echo intensity. meter
temp_c  seawater temperature from ADCP sensor celsius
pressure  pressure measured at the ADCP sensor, measured in decibars with a precision defined as the effective resolution of the instrument. decibar
intensity  ADCP echo intensity (or backscatter), in RDI counts.  This value represents the average of all 4 beams, rounded to the nearest whole number. number

data_quality  A post-processing quantitative data quality indicator.  Specifically, RDI percent-good #4, in earth coordinates (percentage of successful 4-beam transformations), expressed as a percentage, 50, 80, 95, etc. number
eastward  True eastward velocity measurements.  Negative values represent westward velocities. metersPerSecond
northward  True northward velocity measurements.  Negative values represent southward velocities. metersPerSecond
upwards  True upwards velocity measurements.  Negative values represent downward velocities. metersPerSecond
errorvelocity  The difference of two vertical velocities, each measured by an opposing pair of ADCP beams metersPerSecond

pisco_code (pisco code) Six character alphanumeric code which uniquely identifies the site where the intertidal survey was conducted.
SiteID (Site ID) The unique letter code for each site that is referenced by the observation tables.
SiteName (Site name) A list of sites where MARINe surveys were conducted along the West Coast of North America. Each site name corresponds to a unique location.
CountyName (County name) The county in which the site is located.
Island_name (Island name) The name of the island where the referenced site is located. This name includes (but is not limited to) the Channel Islands.

MPA_designation (MPA designation) Describes whether the referenced site is located within a Marine Protected Area (MPA) or is a reference site. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within an MPA, or is not a reference site for an existing MPA site.
MPA_region (MPA region) The name of the MPA region where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within an MPA.
MPA_name (MPA name) The name of the MPA where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within an MPA.
NMS_name (NMS name) The name of the National Marine Sanctuary where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within an NMS.
ASBS_name (ASBS name) The name of the Area of Special Biological Significance where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within an ASBS.

National_designation (National designation) The name of the National Park region (including, but not limited, to Monuments, Recreation Areas, and Seashores) where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within a known National Park region.

State_Province_designation (State or Province designation) The name of the State or Provincial Park region (including, but not limited to, Recreation Areas, State Beaches, and Tribal Lands) where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within a known State or Provincial Park region.

County_designation (County designation) The name of the County Park region (including, but not limited to Preserves and Protected areas) where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within a known County Park region.

other_designation (other designation) The name of the other region (including, but not limited to Ranches, Reserves, Tribal Lands, Military Lands, and Ecological Reserves) where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within a known other region.
County (County) The name of the U.S. County where the referenced site is located. If this field is blank, the referenced site is not located within the United States.
State_Province_Country (State or Province, Country) The State or Province and Country where the referenced site is located.
SiteLatitude (Site latitude) The number of degrees North of the equator, expressed in decimal degrees to 5 decimal places (NAD83). degree
SiteLongitude (Site longitude) The number of degrees West of the Prime Meridian, expressed in decimal degrees to 5 decimal places (NAD83). degree

YearEstablished (Year established) The year the site was established. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

Month Established (Month established) The month that the site was established. This month is expressed in M or MM format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

DayEstablished (Day established) The day of the month that the site was established. This date is expressed in D or DD format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.
NorthSouthOrder (Geographical sort order) Used to order the sites geographically along the coast. Actual values are arbitrary, and should not be used for site identification.
Comments (Comments) Comments specific to each site.
PersonnelID (Personnel ID) The unique alphanumeric code for each person that conducted MARINe surveys. This ID is referenced by the observation tables.
Full Name (Full Name) The first and last name of the person doing the sampling.
GroupCode (Group Code) The unique code for each monitoring group that is referenced by the observation tables.
GroupName (Group Name) The full name used to identify each monitoring group.
MonitoringGroup (Monitoring Group) Defines if the group is a group that conducts monitoring or not.
PersonnelFirstName (Personnel First Name) First name of the person doing the sampling.
PersonnelMiddleInitial (Personnel Middle Initial) Middle initial of the person doing the sampling
PersonnelLastName (Personnel Last Name) Last name of the person doing the sampling
Remarks (Comments) Comments regarding the specific sampler.

OriginalName (Original Name) The name of the taxonomic, functional, morphologic, or geologic concept being observed, as it appears in the data taken from the field. This field documents if multiple organisms have been classified with the same name (lumped). This field also documents any name changes (synonyms). Degree of lumping may vary over time and is reflected in the associated Name Convergence field.
NameConvergence (Name Convergence) The unique name that references the taxonomic, functional, morphologic, or geologic concept being observed. This is the current name designation.
Biological variable (Biological variable) Defines whether the variable in the Name Convergence column is biological or not
Kingdom (Kingdom) One of seven biological categories (such as Plantae or Animalia). This is the broadest resolution of phylogenic identification used in this table.
Phylum_Division (Phylum or Division) The major taxonomic group of animals (phylum) and plants (division); contains classes.
Class (Class) A taxonomic group containing one or more orders.
Order (Order) Taxonomic group containing one or more families.
Family (Family) A taxonomic group containing one or more genera.
Genus (Genus) Taxonomic group containing one or more species.
Species (Species) Taxonomic group whose members can interbreed. This is the most refined level of resolution for phylogenic identification used in this table.
SixLetterCode (Species Code) Unique alphabetic lookup code that is referenced by the observation tables.
PhotoLump (Photo plot lumping code) Six letter code used to lump species together for photo plots across different MARINe survey groups.
TransectLump (Transect lumping code) Six letter code used to lump species together for transect surveys across different MARINe survey groups.
TargetSpecies (Target Species) Defines whether the species observed is a target species. A target species is a species or species group that is targeted by a specific survey protocol.

SpeciesCoreFlag (Species Core Flag) Defines whether the species observed is a core species in one or more more of the survey types. A core species is a species or species group that MARINe researchers have agreed to count in each plot or transect.

PhotoPlotsCoreSpecies (Photo Plots Core Species) Defines whether the species observed is designated as a core species in the photo plot surveys. A core species is a species or species group that MARINe researchers have agreed to count in each plot or transect.

TransectsCoreSpecies (Transects Core Species) Defines whether the species observed is designated as a core species in the transect surveys. A core species is a species or species group that MARINe researchers have agreed to count in each plot or transect.

CircularPlotCoreSpecies (Circular Plot Core Species) Defines whether the species observed is designated as a core species in the circular plot surveys. A core species is a species or species group that MARINe researchers have agreed to count in each plot or transect.

AbaloneSeastarCoreSpecies (Abalone Seastar Core Species) Defines whether the species observed is designated as a core species in the abalone or seastar surveys. A core species is a species or species group that MARINe researchers have agreed to count in each plot or transect.
GroupCode (Group Code) The unique code for the monitoring group that surveys the referenced plot at a given site. This code refers to a specific group listed on the personnel table.
SiteID (Site ID) The unique letter code that indicates where the plot is located. This ID refers to a specific entry in the site table.
TargetSpecies (Target Species) The specific organism that this plot was created to monitor.
PlotID (Plot Number) Replicate plot number, starting from 1.
PlotArea (Plot Area) The area of the plot. meter
MethodCode (Method) The method used for sampling the plot.

CountSizePlotYearEstablished (Year Established) The year this plot configuration was established. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

CountSizePlotMonthEstablished (Month Established) The month this plot configuration was established. This month is expressed in M or MM format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

CountSizePlotDayEstablished (Day Established) The day of the month this plot configuration was established. This date is expressed in D or DD format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

CountSizePlotEffectiveEndYear (Effective End Year) The last year this configuration was effective. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

CountSizePlotEffectiveEndMonth (Effective End Month) The last month this configuration was effective. This month is expressed in M or MM format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

CountSizePlotEffectiveEndDay (Effective End Day) The last day of the month that this configuration was effective. This date is expressed in D or DD format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.
GroupCode (Group Code) The unique code for the monitoring group that surveys the referenced plot at a given site. This code refers to a specific group listed on the personnel table.
SiteID (Site ID) The unique letter code that indicates where the transect is located. This ID refers to a specific entry in the site table.
TargetSpecies (Target Species) The specific organism that this plot was created to monitor.
PlotID (Plot Number) Replicate plot number, starting from 1.
PhotoPlotArea (Plot Area) The area of the plot in square meters (m2). meter

YearEstablished (Year Established) The year this plot configuration was established. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

MonthEstablished (Month Established) The month this plot configuration was established. This month is expressed in M or MM format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

DayEstablished (Day Established) The day of the month this plot configuration was established. This date is expressed in D or DD format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

EffectiveEndYear (Effective End Year) The last year this configuration was effective. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

EffectiveEndMonth (Effective End Month) The last month this configuration was effective. This month is expressed in M or MM format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

EffectiveEndDay (Effective End Day) The last day of the month that this configuration was effective. This date is expressed in D or DD format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.
Comments (Comments) Supporting remarks regarding the specific plot being surveyed.
GroupCode (Group Code) The unique code for each monitoring group. This code refers to a specific group listed on the personnel table.
SiteID (Site ID) The unique letter code that indicates where the survey was performed. This ID refers to a specific entry in the site table.
SampleSeason (Sample Season) Consecutive sampling number. A code created to allow sequencing of the seasons, used for sorting data in chronological order.
SamplingSeasonCode (Sampling season code) A four-character code to identify the Sampling season. The first two characters indicate the season and the last 2 characters indicate the year

SampleYear (Sample season year) The four digit calendar year for this sample season. The sample season is designated by the survey team, and may not indicate the actual survey year. For example, surveys conducted in January, 2008 may have a sample season year of 2007. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.
SeasonSeq (Season Sequence) The Season sequence within each year. Each number indicates a different season.

SurveyYear (Survey Year) The year the observation took place. This year is expressed in YYYY format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

SurveyMonth (Survey Month) The month the observation took place. This month is expressed in M or MM format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.

SurveyDay (Survey Day) The day of the month that the observation took place. This date is expressed in D or DD format. Dates reflect measurements taken in local time. Local time is Pacific Standard Time except during months when Pacific Daylight Time is effective.
TargetSpecies (Target Species) The specific organism that this plot was created to monitor.
PlotID (Plot Number) Replicate plot number, starting from 1.
SixLetterCode (Species code) The unique code that indicates the organism or characteristic being identified. This code refers to a specific entry on the classification table.
SpeciesCount (Species Count) The count per plot of the organism being counted. dimensionless
SeaStarColor (Sea Star Color) The color of the seastar, if the species being counted is Pisaster ochraceus. If the species counted is not Pisaster ochraceus, this field is blank.
CountQualifier (Qualifier) Used to modify the associated numeric field (counts/percent encountered).

SpeciesSize (Species Size) The size of the species being counted, to the nearest millimeter. Some species are measured using 5 or 10 millimeter bins, such as abalone and Pisaster ochraceus. Only some of the species counted are measured. millimeter
SizeQualifier (Size Qualifier) A description of the size.
MethodCode (Method Code) The method used for the plot.
